metadata.name: floating
metadata.description:
I spent last week at a rental bungalow in Ocean Beach (San Diego), California, for a much needed battery recharge. Most of the time, I just sat on the beach and watched the waves, and admired the different sets of circumstances that could lead to different results. I am continually bemused by how generative art is just creating algorithms to do what nature does fine on its own. 

Waves going out, waves coming in. High tide, low tide. Onshore wind, offshore wind. Strong breeze, gentle breeze. Sun is up, sun is down. Apply fxrand() to all these factors, and here we are. 

Created in p5.js.

metadata.name: Cuts
metadata.description:
Cuts is an abstract representation of the exact moments in our lives when something is cut. It could be moving to a different country, being fired, quitting a bad habit, when a relationship ends or when you receive a very bad (or good!) news.
By themselves, cuts are not positive or negative events; it really depends on who you were before and who you wish to be after. But one thing is sure: every cut creates a new space that wasn’t there. This space could be small or huge, ordered or chaotic, regardless, you have to deal with it. Sometimes cuts try to resist and heal themselves extruding the core of the fibres we are made of, but they will fail. A cut is irreversible and it’s up to us to fill the gap with meaning.

Main features include:
- Curated palettes (21)
- Drawing modes (3)
- Extrusions (yes/no)
- Orientation (3)
- Overlapping (yes/no)
- Covered area (2)
- Cut position (2)

In live mode:
- Press [s] to save a 2400x2400 px image
- Press [t] to toggle shading (sometimes flat colours rock!)
- Press [c] to see copyright notice
- Press [f] to log features in console

By Todemashi 2022
NFT License 2.0

### NOTES
Made with p5js and GLSL shaders.
Shaders are based on tutorials and code by Patricio Gonzalez Vivo - The Book of Shaders - https://thebookofshaders.com/

metadata.name: Self-Portraits
metadata.description:
Images reinterpreted by particles. The direction of each particle changes according to different calculations that use the brightness gradient of the image as an input.

Variations:
Particles speed, initial moving direction, and the way they interact with the image. 
5 different selfies, 5 color modes, 5 dark background colors and a mirror mode.

Press "P" to toggle particle mode.

Inspired by some works of Leonardo Solaas.

metadata.description:
Araucaria forests have existed for more than 200 million years since the Jurassic period, before the separation of America and Africa. These trees are spread across South America from Argentina to the northeast of Brazil. This artwork creates with pure code a landscape of Araucaria trees inspired by Serra da Mantiqueira.

As florestas de Araucárias existem há mais de 200 milhões de anos desde o período Jurássico, antes da separação entre América e África. Essas árvores estão espalhadas pela América do Sul desde a Argentina até o nordeste do Brasil. Essa obra cria com código puro uma paisagem de araucárias  inspirada na Serra da Mantiqueira.

Features:

9 color palettes, Density of Araucaria trees, Clouds.

Created by Zydron using P5js.

metadata.name: Heaven & Hell
metadata.description:
Heaven & Hell is a companion work to my genesis mint on fxhash, Doors of Perception.

Doors of Perception was inspired by Aldous Huxley's book of the same name, the title taken from William Blake's metaphor for his own book 'The Marriage Of Heaven & Hell'. As you can see below, this metaphor is self explanatory...

“If the doors of perception were cleansed every thing would appear to man as it is, Infinite. For man has closed himself up, till he sees all things thro’ narrow chinks of his cavern”

Taking mythology as my guide, I have created two distinct colour palettes for both Heaven, and Hell. Heaven is split to 7 layers, and Hell into 9.

———————————

- Layers are randomly determined to between 1 and 7 or 9 respectively
- Each iteration generates an infinite non-looping output from the determined colours at mint
- Image adjusts to all screen ratios
- 1137 randomly allocated colours 
- Code size at 252 kb
- Press 's' key to save as 'Heaven & Hell.png'

Rarity will only be determined once the collection has minted out.

Choose wisely...

metadata.name: Cascade
metadata.description:
This piece is heavily influenced by the Danish physicist Per Bak and his work on self-organized criticality.

Specifically, it is derivative of his sandpile model. In that model, grains of sand are added to a grid at random locations. If the number of grains at a single location exceeds four, it begins an "avalanche", and pushes one grain out to each cardinal neighbor. This then has the potential of causing a string of avalanches as neighbors also exceed the limit.

His model has a number of interesting characteristics, the most noteworthy being that regardless of initial configuration, it eventually approaches a critical state where the frequency of avalanches sizes follows a power-law relationship. Avalanches of any size are possible, with their frequencies being inversely proportional to the size of the avalanche.

'Cascade' has some important distinctions from this sandpile model.

- Cascades can happen as soon as there are three grains of sand rather than four in a given cell
- Cascades will not flow back into the neighboring location(s) that caused a cell to exceed its threshold
- New grains are introduced at one or more fixed locations rather than randomly

I've provided the following keyboard shortcuts to allow you to explore this system more thoroughly:
'P': pause/play
Right Arrow: Take a single step forward
'S': Restart with new set of sand sources
'I': Restart with new initial sand configuration
'C': Toggle whether or not circles are drawn
'L': Toggle whether or not lines are shown when sand moves
'T': Toggle text indicating how many grains of sand are present

metadata.name: Pixel Blobs
metadata.description:
Each design features a preconfigured pattern of pixel blobs that slowly consume the canvas creating abstract pixel art. Canvases are also interactive and allow designers to create their own abstract art.

- 'c' clears the canvas
- click and drag to paint pixel blob pattern
- '0-9' changes the paint color
- 'ENTER' allows blobs to grow until the canvas is covered
- 'SPACE' pauses growth
- 'g' toggles grid lines on/off
- 's' saves the canvas as a png to mint or share

Pixel Blobs is a collaboration with Austin Pocus.

Coming soon: We're developing an interactive game based on Pixel Blobs. Follow @RasterlyNFT on Twitter for more details.

100% of primary sales will go to a smart contract (KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx) that will direct the funds to a list of NGOs supporting Ukraine. This contract has been set up as a joint effort by fxhash and Versum.

The proceedings will be donated to these NGO's:
https://twitter.com/TheGivingBlock/status/1496910223034155008

metadata.name: Stairs
metadata.description:
Algorithmically generated stairs. Inspired by Dutch graphic artist M.C. Escher.

Arrangement, style and color set are unique in each edition.

However:
Any edition can generate an infinite amount of arrangements & styles and allows you to cycle through the color sets, so that you can find your perfect piece. 
The preview is based on the initial, randomized arrangement & style.


Created in Vanilla JS on Canvas2D

Controls:
R - Generate Stairs
B - Change Background
C - Change Color
D - Change Style
A - Restart Animation
S - Download Image


DUTCH AUCTION:
The price will start out at 5ꜩ and will decrease by 1ꜩ every 10 minutes. It will remain at 1ꜩ.
